Bellabeat_Case_Study

Ashley Hogden

2022-04-17

Ask

Business task: Analyze FitBit user data from April to May 2016 to identify trends in smart device usage, apply it to Bellabeat’s customers, and influence their marketing strategy.

What are some trends in smart device usage?

How can these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?

How can these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

In this case study, I utilized a FitBit user dataset that contains data from the personal fitness trackers of thirty FitBit users. These individuals consented to the usage of their personal data, including but not limited to information like minute-by-minute physical activity, steps, heartrate, and sleep data. In addition, more comprehensive data about each user’s day was included as well. For instance, activity level, distance, minutes and so much more were tracked, which can be used to analyze the habits of these users.

Prepare data

To begin, I needed to install and load the following packages: tidyverse, dplyr, and lubridate.

I also uploaded each table from the dataset in CSV format to the R Studio Environment.

Analysis and visualization

Sleep data
ggplot(data = sleep, aes(x = TotalTimeInBed, y = TotalMinutesAsleep)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Time in Bed versus Time Asleep", x = "Time in Bed", y = "Time Asleep")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The plot above illustrates a correlation between time in bed and minutes asleep that begins to plateau at about 700 minutes asleep or 875 minutes in bed. Thus, more time in bed doesn’t always correlate more minutes asleep.

ggplot(data = dailydata_sleepall, aes(x = TotalTimeInBed, y = TotalMinutesAsleep)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + facet_wrap(~DailyActivityLevel) + labs(title = "Time in Bed versus Time Asleep by Activity Level", x = "Time in Bed", y = "Time Asleep")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The graph above shows the time in bed versus time asleep per activity level. It illustrates that uses who had sedentary days experienced the plateau of the positive correlation between minutes asleep and time in bed. It even becomes a negative correlation once they have spent more than 875 minutes in bed. This means a portion of their extra sedentary time could be coming from their time in bed before or after sleeping.

In addition, the users’ sedentary days are the sole contributors to the plateau of the correlation in the overall graph. This can be seen by examining that the positive correlations between the two variables does not plateau for other activity levels.

ggplot(data = dailydata_sleepall, aes(x = TotalTimeInBed, y = TotalMinutesAsleep)) + facet_wrap(~VeryActiveStatus) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Time in Bed versus Time Asleep by Very Active Frequency", x = "Time in Bed", y = "Time Asleep")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The plot above illustrates a similar concept, except from the angle of frequency of time spent at a very active level. Indeed, users who spend a low amount of time as very active tend to see the positive correlation between time in bed and time asleep turn into a negative correlation.

ggplot(data = dailydata_sleepall, aes(x = TotalTimeInBed, y = TotalMinutesAsleep)) + facet_wrap(~SedentaryActiveStatus) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Time in Bed versus Time Asleep by Sedentary Activity Frequency", x = "Time in Bed", y = "Time Asleep")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

This can be seen yet again in the plot above, where higher amounts of sedentary time result in a positive correlation between minutes asleep and time in bed that plateaus. In contrast, lower amounts of sedentary time do not see the same plateau.

Act

A study examining sedentary behavior and cardiovascular disease in older women concluded that “high sedentary time and mean bout durations were associated…with increased CVD [cardiovascular disease] risk in older women, which suggests that efforts to reduce CVD burden might benefit from addressing either or both components of sedentary behavior” (Bellettiere et al., 2019). Bellabeat is a company aimed at empowering women with the knowledge of their own health and habits. As a result, it is vital that Bellabeat grasps the trend in this FitBit data that sedentary time is detrimental to the health of the users because it is associated with fewer calories burned, lower amounts of physical activity, and therefore increased risk of CVD, according to Bellettiere et al. (2019). Thus, Bellabeat has a very necessary role to fill in the lives of their female customers. When their customers are utilizing the Leaf or Time products, Bellabeat should send them notifications via the app if those products detect prolonged sedentary time. By doing this, Bellabeat can market its products as healthcare devices that will aid in combating cardiovascular disease among its female userbase.

Another feature that could stem the excess time in bed, and thus sedentary time, would be a bedtime and wake up feature. This will allow users to set the time they would like to go to bed and wake up, with notifications that communicate to them the optimal moments for both so that excessive time is not spent in bed before or after sleeping. This would be beneficial to the heart health of Bellabeat’s female audience because “sedentary behavior guidelines in several industrialized countries and recommendations from the American Diabetes Association call for an overall reduction in sedentary time and for regular interruption of long sedentary bouts” (Bellettiere et al., 2019). In this way, users can be encouraged to break up those bouts of sedentary time that can increase the risk of CVD.

One final addition that Bellabeat’s app could incorporate is a set of factoids about health that align with that user’s activity level. This could include findings from peer-reviewed studies such as the one quoted in this case study to empower users with the knowledge of their health, thus aligning with Bellabeat’s mission. Giving users these important factoids can be even more encouragement to get up and move around, as they will understand the long-term affects of their behavior on their health and mortality. Bolstering their own data with outsider peer-reviewed studies regarding cardiovascular health can add further merit to their devices as healthcare-focused when updating Bellabeat’s marketing strategy.

As for next steps, Bellabeat should begin by doing research into peer-reviewed studies to examine other health benefits to physical activity and the detriment that sedentary activity does to one’s body. Then, they can incorporate this information into alerts on the users’ phones when they have been sedentary too long. Bellabeat can then finally update their marketing materials to reveal their new, more healthcare-focused and science-backed approach to the wearable fitness device space.

Additional data that can expand on my findings would be data from Bellabeat’s current products. It could be beneficial to examine the current user base for Bellabeat, alongside the FitBit data, for more plentiful, verifiable first-hand data. This way, other factors like age and gender can be examined to make further conclusions about the importance of these findings within the health of Bellabeat’s target audience of women.
